  abstract = {Due to incomplete contracts, efficiency of an organization depends on willingness of\$\textbackslash{}backslash\$nindividuals to take non-selfish actions, e.g., cooperate when there is no incentive to do so, or\$\textbackslash{}backslash\$npunish inefficient actions by others. Organizations also constitute a social boundary, or\$\textbackslash{}backslash\$ngroup. We investigate whether this social aspect of organizations has an important benefit,\$\textbackslash{}backslash\$nfostering unselfish cooperation and norm enforcement within the group, but whether there is\$\textbackslash{}backslash\$nalso a dark side, in the form of hostility between groups. Our experiment provides the first\$\textbackslash{}backslash\$nevidence without the confounding effect of self-selection into groups. Individuals are\$\textbackslash{}backslash\$nrandomly assigned to different platoons during a four-week portion of officer training in the\$\textbackslash{}backslash\$nSwiss Army. We conduct choice experiments \textendash{} simultaneous prisoner's dilemma games, with\$\textbackslash{}backslash\$nand without third-party punishment \textendash{} in week three. Random assignment significantly\$\textbackslash{}backslash\$nincreases willingness to cooperate with fellow platoon members. Assignment does not lead to\$\textbackslash{}backslash\$nhostility, in the sense of vindictive punishment of outsiders, but does affect norm\$\textbackslash{}backslash\$nenforcement, enhancing willingness to enforce a norm of cooperation towards fellow platoon\$\textbackslash{}backslash\$nmembers. This suggests that the social aspect of organizations motivates efficient behavior\$\textbackslash{}backslash\$neven when ordinary incentives fail, and helps explain practices designed to foster social ties\$\textbackslash{}backslash\$nor group identification within an organization.},
